	var comments={
			3327: {
				id_comment: 3327,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘Their due’, including their maintenance by public alms, according to the custom of the early Church (cf. Ac. 6.1). In Heb., the verb ‘to honour’ sometimes has the sense of monetary payment (cf. Ecclus. 38.1, and p. 16, note 2)."
			},
					3328: {
				id_comment: 3328,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘She must be warned’; the Greek manuscripts, and many of the Latin, have ‘they must be warned’. This seems the more probable reading, in view of verse 7."
			},
					3329: {
				id_comment: 3329,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘Would be alive and dead both at once’; literally, ‘is dead while she still lives’. The sense appears to be, that she must not attempt to live a worldly life and claim, at the same time, the privileges of widowhood."
			},
					3330: {
				id_comment: 3330,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "There is the same uncertainty here as in 3.2 above."
			},
					3331: {
				id_comment: 3331,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "This verse is ordinarily translated ‘When they have begun to grow wanton against Christ’, but this does not translate the Latin, and is a very doubtful rendering of the Greek. St Paul surely means, ‘When they have finished living a luxurious life, upon the alms of the Christian community’."
			},
					3332: {
				id_comment: 3332,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘Consideration’ here is the same word in Greek as ‘their due’ in verse 3 above, and is no doubt used partly in the same signification; cf. the verse which follows."
			},
					3333: {
				id_comment: 3333,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "Deut. 25.4; see also Mt. 10.10."
			},
					3334: {
				id_comment: 3334,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "‘To those’, probably meaning ‘to those presbyters’; and the direction that they are to be rebuked in public is best understood as meaning ‘Before the other presbyters’."
			},
					3335: {
				id_comment: 3335,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "St Timothy is probably warned against ordaining presbyters without due enquiry into their character; but it seems that the imposition of hands was also used in remitting ecclesiastical censures, and some think this is the meaning here."
			},
					3336: {
				id_comment: 3336,
				source_str: '✻',
				caption: '',
				content: "This sentence interrupts the drift of the passage; probably St Paul suddenly remembered a question put to him, and answered it, as it were, in a foot-note."
			},
